Insertion points allow users to effortlessly include preconfigured content (building blocks) into the document. Insertion points are indicated by blue/orange labels on the document side:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Insertion point labels*

By clicking on the label, the right side panel is opened. From there, the user can invoke various building block operations which we will now discuss.

## Working with the Insertion Points
### Adding of the Building Blocks
To add the building block, simply drag and drop it from the right side panel into the document or click on the add button:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Building block drag and drop*

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Building block add button*

Building blocks are by default a protected area, which is not interactive to encourage the use of parameters. This is also very important in more complicated scenarios to prevent the user from accidentally losing content when they refresh or modify building block parameters.

If the building block is configured to have parameters, during the drag and drop operation or after clicking the add button, the user will get a dialog in which it is possible to customize the look of the building block:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Building block edit dialog*

The ability to insert building blocks multiple times is configurable and might be limited to enforce the designed intent of the insertion point. This causes the add button to be disabled, and drag and drop is no longer possible, preventing the user from making a mistake.

There is a convenient preview feature available that allows the user to see how the building block will look before it is inserted. To invoke the preview, click on the preview button in the right side panel:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Building block preview button*

### Moving of the Building Blocks
Building blocks can be moved in the editor by dragging and dropping the left 'puzzle- looking' icon. The valid drop target is only the same insertion point. Users cannot move building blocks from one insertion point to another:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Moving of building block*

### Removing of the Building Blocks
Users can remove a building block by clicking on the bin icon in the editor or by clicking the bin icon in the right side panel. Note that the remove button in the editor only appears after the user has selected the building block by clicking on the 'puzzle-looking' icon.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Remove building block in editor and side panel button*

### Refreshing of the Building Blocks
It is possible to refresh the content of a building block by clicking the refresh icon. The content of the building block will be refreshed and replace the previous building block. Users need to be careful if they made changes to the previous content. If they detect a problem, undo is always available.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Refresh building block button*

### Modifying of the Building Blocks
Modification of building block parameters is possible with the edit button in the right side panel or by double-clicking the building block 'puzzle-looking' icon in the editor. Both operations will invoke the edit parameters dialog, which updates the building block after the dialog closes. Note that similarly to the refresh feature, modification will overwrite previous building block content.
